1. Open your Google Sheets file.
2. Click on "Extensions" in the top menu, and then select "Apps Script".
3. In the Apps Script editor, replace any existing code with the following script:

```javascript
function updateTime() {
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActive().getActiveSheet();
  var referenceCell = sheet.getRange("A1");
  var timestampCell = sheet.getRange("B1");

  if (referenceCell.getValue() === true) {
    var timeZone = SpreadsheetApp.getActive().getSpreadsheetTimeZone();
    var timestamp = Utilities.formatDate(new Date(), timeZone, "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss");
    timestampCell.setValue(timestamp);
  }
}

function onEdit(e) {
  updateTime();
}
```

4. Save the script by clicking on the floppy disk icon or by pressing "Ctrl + S".
5. Close the Apps Script editor.

Now, whenever cell A1 is edited, the script will automatically update the timestamp in cell B1 with the current time in Central Daylight Time (CDT). If cell A1 is false, the timestamp will not be updated.

Note that the script uses the "onEdit" trigger, which will update the timestamp only when there's an actual edit in cell A1. If you want the timestamp to update even if A1 is changed programmatically, you can also manually run the "updateTime" function by clicking on "Run" in the top menu and selecting "updateTime".

